If you're going to write in paragraphs please break to a new line whenever there is a new speaker. It's a simple style thing that makes reading easier for your audience.

Pulling an example out from your text:
>“Monin’ Anon, are you doing alright so far?” He replies in the thickest South-Georgian accent you’ve heard in your life. “I reckon I’m doing just fine Mr. M-” You trail off as you struggle to remember his very complicated and long-winded last name. He smirks and gives a dismissive wave of his hand. “Oh don’t worry ‘bout it. Everybody jus’ call me Gregory, only met a few people who’ve ever managed it on the first try.” The gator moves out from behind the counter to stroll up beside you, despite his old age he’s still much taller and a bit bulkier than you. “So, I’m assumin’ you’re here about your new livin’ arrangements?” He asked, strolling over to the front door. “Yessir.” You reply quickly, following him outside when he pushes the door open.

Versus a more readable:
>“Monin’ Anon, are you doing alright so far?” He replies in the thickest South-Georgian accent you’ve heard in your life.
>“I reckon I’m doing just fine Mr. M-” You trail off as you struggle to remember his very complicated and long-winded last name. He smirks and gives a dismissive wave of his hand.
>“Oh don’t worry ‘bout it. Everybody jus’ call me Gregory, only met a few people who’ve ever managed it on the first try.” The gator moves out from behind the counter to stroll up beside you, despite his old age he’s still much taller and a bit bulkier than you. “So, I’m assumin’ you’re here about your new livin’ arrangements?” He asked, strolling over to the front door.
>“Yessir.” You reply quickly, following him outside when he pushes the door open.

Regarding exposition: I can understand the desire to get it out of the way quickly and more or less at once. Sometimes that's a good idea, but you may want to consider revealing that sort of context as it becomes relevant to the active scene, or at least delay it until the first real scene is established. The general wisdom is to "start in the action". In your particular case, I might even consider simply starting the whole narrative earlier chronologically, and actually letting us experience some of the stuff outright. Something like the tiger mugging I might like to actually see rather than hear about, particularly because it's so recent. Events in your exposition should not be more interesting than events in the action. If they are, why aren't we reading about them instead? That's the kind of thing that stimulates tl;dr, above length itself.

I'm just a humble writefag, but my general approach to exposition is to have very little of it, have it serve the plot, and, if you can help it, start with as little as possible. Like you said, "start in the action" is generally the best approach

A couple lines of really well-written, scene-setting exposition can enhance a piece's opening a lot, but it has to be just that -- exceedingly interesting and well-written. I've edited a LOT of people's creative writing, both professionally and personally, and I always see exposition dumps that need to be broken out into actual dialogue or prose. It's a pretty novice mistake that I'm just as guilty of, but one that can instantly kill a reader's interest in the story.

I've not read the piece in question yet, but I will read a few grafs to see.
